matrix (elements should always keep the same)

mat <- matrix(1:20, ncol = 4)
mat
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    1    6   11   16
## [2,]    2    7   12   17
## [3,]    3    8   13   18
## [4,]    4    9   14   19
## [5,]    5   10   15   20
# pick up a single element
mat[5,2]
## [1] 10
# pick up a col
mat[,3]
## [1] 11 12 13 14 15
#pick up a row
mat[2,]
## [1]  2  7 12 17
#pick up several rows
mat[2:4,]
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    2    7   12   17
## [2,]    3    8   13   18
## [3,]    4    9   14   19
# reassign the value
mat[4,] <- rep(100,4)
mat
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    1    6   11   16
## [2,]    2    7   12   17
## [3,]    3    8   13   18
## [4,]  100  100  100  100
## [5,]    5   10   15   20
# name the col name
colnames(mat) <- c('one','two','three','four')
mat
##      one two three four
## [1,]   1   6    11   16
## [2,]   2   7    12   17
## [3,]   3   8    13   18
## [4,] 100 100   100  100
## [5,]   5  10    15   20
mat[,'four']
## [1]  16  17  18 100  20
# name the row name
rownames(mat) <- c('a','b','c','d','e')
mat
##   one two three four
## a   1   6    11   16
## b   2   7    12   17
## c   3   8    13   18
## d 100 100   100  100
## e   5  10    15   20
# tick out some elements
mat[,c(-1,-2)]
##   three four
## a    11   16
## b    12   17
## c    13   18
## d   100  100
## e    15   20

mylist

## [1] 3

## $mat

## [2,]    2    4
## 
## $morestuff
## [1] "china" "japan"
## 
## [[4]]
## [[4]][[1]]
## [1] 5
## 
## [[4]][[2]]
## [1] "bear"
class(mylist)
## [1] "list"
# three way to pick the component in the list
mylist[['stuff']]
## [1] 3
mylist$stuff
## [1] 3
mylist[1]
## $stuff
## [1] 3
mylist[2:4]
## $mat
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    3
## [2,]    2    4
## 
## $morestuff
## [1] "china" "japan"
## 
## [[3]]
## [[3]][[1]]
## [1] 5
## 
## [[3]][[2]]
## [1] "bear"
# two way to pick the element in some component
mylist$stuff[1] == mylist[[1]]
## [1] TRUE

remove the NA

t <- c(-1,0,NA,5) 
mean(t)
## [1] NA
mean(t,na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 1.333333
## null is just do not exist
s <- c(-1,0,NULL,5) 
mean(s)
## [1] 1.333333
## to judge whether it is na
is.na(t)
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE
## inf and not a nuber(nan)
c(3/0,0/0)
## [1] Inf NaN
is.na(c(3/0,0/0))
## [1] FALSE  TRUE
## define an empty vector
x = NULL
x[1] = 'blue'
x[2] = 'red'
x[4] = 'green'
x
## [1] "blue"  "red"   NA      "green"

split the data according to the factor

ages <- c(20,30,40,35,35,35,35)
sex  <- c('M','M','F','M','F','F','F')
split(ages,sex)
## $F
## [1] 40 35 35 35
## 
## $M
## [1] 20 30 35
## use split() to list ages in each group + sex pair
list(group,sex)
## [[1]]
## [1] control   control   control   treatment treatment treatment treatment
## Levels: control treatment
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "M" "M" "F" "M" "F" "F" "F"
split(ages,list(group,sex))
## $control.F
## [1] 40
## 
## $treatment.F
## [1] 35 35 35
## 
## $control.M
## [1] 20 30
## 
## $treatment.M
## [1] 35
# split() has coerced sex into a factor variable]
table(sex,group)
##    group
## sex control treatment
##   F       1         3
##   M       2         1
# most matrix operations work on tables as well
new_table <- table(sex, group)
new_table[, "control"]
## F M 
## 1 2
round(new_table/length(group), 3) 
##    group
## sex control treatment
##   F   0.143     0.429
##   M   0.286     0.143

DataFrame(each col can have different classes)

# stringAsFactors = TRUE, automatically change all the string into factor
name <- c('john','jill','jacob','jenny')
year <- c(1,1,2,4)
grade <- c('B','A+','B-','A')
student_data <- data.frame(name,year,grade,stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
student_data
##    name year grade
## 1  john    1     B
## 2  jill    1    A+
## 3 jacob    2    B-
## 4 jenny    4     A
dim(student_data)
## [1] 4 3
str(student_data)
## 'data.frame':    4 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ name : chr  "john" "jill" "jacob" "jenny"
##  $ year : num  1 1 2 4
##  $ grade: chr  "B" "A+" "B-" "A"

##    name year grade
## 3 jacob    2    B-

student_data$name
## [1] "john"  "jill"  "jacob" "jenny"
student_data$school <- 'columbia'
student_data

findwords <- function(text_vec){
words <- split(1:length(text_vec), text_vec)
return(words)
}
wordlist <- findwords(HC)
wordlist$students
## [1]   1  48 142 204 232 310 331
alphabetized_list <- function(wordlist) {
        nms <- names(wordlist) # The names are the words
        sorted <- sort(nms)
        # The words, but now in ABC order
        return(wordlist[sorted]) # Returns the sorted version
}
alphabetized_list(wordlist)
